{"type":"message","id":"d62fb358","parentId":"86775502","timestamp":"2026-02-17T20:33:46.332Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Tue 2026-02-17 14:33 CST] === Tetris Level 2 - Episode 9 Report === |  | CURRENT STATE: |   Lines cleared this episode: 12 |   Pieces placed: 6 |   Board: 6x12 |   Pieces available: O, I |  | PERFORMANCE TREND (last 10 episodes): |   Mean lines: 6.7 |   Best: 12  Worst: 2 |   Trend: IMPROVING (+48%) |   Consistency: MEDIUM |  | BOARD STATE (end of episode): |   Column heights: [12, 12, 12, 12, 12, 12] |   Aggregate height: 72 |   Holes: 0 |   Bumpiness: 0 |   Max height: 12/12 |   Avg row completeness: 100% |   Board top (cols 0-5): |   |######| |   |######| |   |######| |   |######| |   |######| |   |######| |  | FAILURE ANALYSIS: |   - 10/10 episodes died within 10 pieces (board fills too fast) |  | HYPOTHESIS PERFORMANCE: |   No hypothesis profiles yet |  | DREAMER STATUS: |   Reliance: N/A |   Dream interval: N/A |   Active options: 0 |   Best hypothesis: N/A |  | QUESTIONS - Please respond with SPECIFIC actionable advice: |   1. Given the board state and failure pattern, what SPECIFIC |      placement strategy should we try? (e.g. 'prioritize filling |      column 3 gaps before building height elsewhere') |   2. Which hypothesis should we STOP using and why? |   3. Suggest a NEW micro-hypothesis in this format: |      'When [board condition], do [specific placement action]'"}],"timestamp":1771360426306}}
{"type":"message","id":"a879facf","parentId":"d62fb358","timestamp":"2026-02-17T20:34:16.633Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is interesting - the episode data changed slightly. Episode 9 now shows 12 lines cleared (was 22 before), 6 pieces placed (was 7), mean is now 6.7 (was 5.2), and trend is +48% (was +450%).\n\nThe core problem is still the same though: the board fills to max height (12/12 all columns) with perfect structure (0 holes, 0 bumpiness, 100% completeness) but dies from height in under 10 pieces.\n\nThe agent is clearing lines efficiently (12 lines in 6 pieces = 2 lines/piece average) but it's still dying from height. The issue is that it's building too fast without creating space.\n\nLet me give fresh analysis based on this specific data.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"text","text":"## Episode 9 Analysis: Efficient Clearing, Fatal Height Management\n\n### 🔍 **Pattern Recognition**\n\n**Good news:** 12 lines in 6 pieces = 2 lines/piece (excellent efficiency)  \n**Bad news:** Board maxed at 12/12 height across ALL columns = no recovery space\n\n**Root cause:** Agent clears lines WHILE building to full height simultaneously. It's like bailing water while the boat is already sinking.\n\n---\n\n### 1. **SPECIFIC Placement Strategy: \"Height Ceiling Discipline\"**\n\n```\nNEVER let ANY column exceed height 10 (leave 2 rows buffer)\n\nImplementation:\n- Before placing, check: will this make any column > 10?\n- If YES: reject that placement, force placement in shortest column\n- If NO: proceed with normal scoring (completeness, flatness, etc.)\n```\n\n**Applied to your board:**\n- With O and I pieces available and 6x12 board\n- **O-piece rule:** Only place in columns currently at height ≤ 8 (leaves 2-row O + 2-row buffer)\n- **I-piece rule:** Place HORIZONTALLY in rows 9-10 to complete lines and DROP height\n\n**Why this fixes it:** You're clearing efficiently but have 0 safety margin. One bad piece and it's game over. The 2-row buffer gives you room to recover.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Which Hypothesis to STOP Using**\n\n**STOP: Whatever is driving \"fill to max height\"**\n\nYour board shows 100% row completeness at death — this suggests an implicit \"maximize completion at all heights\" policy. \n\n**The bug:** It's building UP without creating SPACE.\n\n**Replace with:** \"Never exceed height threshold\" as a HARD CONSTRAINT (not a scored preference, an absolute rule)\n\n---\n\n### 3. **NEW Micro-Hypothesis**\n\n```\n'When max_height >= 9, ONLY place pieces that either:\n (A) complete at least 1 row, OR\n (B) place in the lowest column if no completion possible'\n```\n\n**Why this works:**\n- **Condition trigger:** Height 9+ means danger zone (3 rows from death)\n- **Action A:** Prioritize clearing to drop height back down\n- **Action B:** If can't clear, at least don't make it worse (fill lowest = maintain some flatness)\n- **What it prevents:** Building higher when already at risk\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Critical Insight: The \"Perfect Death\" Trap**\n\nYour agent achieves **structurally perfect boards** (0 holes, 0 bumps, 100% complete) but this is a **failure mode**, not success.\n\n**Tetris reality:** You need **strategic imperfection** to survive:\n- Leave gaps for specific piece types (I-piece wells)\n- Accept temporary bumpiness to keep height low\n- Value survival > aesthetics\n\n**Reframe the objective:**\n```\nOLD: Maximize completeness + minimize holes + minimize bumpiness\nNEW: Maximize game length (pieces placed) THEN optimize structure\n```\n\nThis flips the priority: stay alive FIRST, build pretty SECOND.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Actionable Next Step**\n\n**Implement \"Height Limiter\" wrapper:**\n\n```python\ndef valid_placements(piece, board):\n    placements = get_all_placements(piece, board)\n    # HARD FILTER: reject any placement creating column > 10\n    safe = [p for p in placements if max_height_after(p) <= 10]\n    return safe if safe else [lowest_column_placement(piece)]\n```\n\n**Expected outcome:**\n- Episodes last 15+ pieces (currently dying at <10)\n- Mean lines increase to 10+ (more time = more clears)\n- Worst-case improves from 2 → 6+ lines (floor rises)\n\nTest this and report: do episodes survive longer, even if structure gets messier?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-5","usage":{"input":10,"output":1117,"cacheRead":40292,"cacheWrite":1190,"totalTokens":42609,"cost":{"input":0.00003,"output":0.016755,"cacheRead":0.012087599999999999,"cacheWrite":0.0044625,"total":0.0333351}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1771360426322}}
